Kotlin uses two different keywords to declare variables: val and var

val - this is for a variable whose value never changes. (IMMUTABLE)
var - this is for a variable whose value can change. (MUTABLE)

Different Kotlin Data Types
- Numbers
- Characters
- Booleans
- Strings
- Arrays

INTEGER - store whole numbers, positive or negative, without decimals. (-2147483648 to 2147483647)
var wholeNumber : Int = 10

BYTE - this data type can store whole numbers from -128 to 127.
val myNum: Byte = 100

SHORT - Short data type can store whole numbers from -32768 to 32767:
val myNum: Short = 5000

LONG - data type can store whole numbers from -9223372036854775807 to 9223372036854775807
val myNum: Long = 15000000000L

The Float and Double data types can store fractional numbers
var decimalNumber : Float = 10.00F
var doubleNumber : Double = 10.23

STRING - holds sequence of character
var charSequence : String = "Llander"

CHARACTER
var oneChar : Char = 'L'

BOOLEAN - holds the value "true" and "false"
var bool : Boolean = true



